# Implement Entropy Peak Penalty

The goal is to ensure that any individual functional component with a complexity (entropy) greater than 15 causes a direct health penalty, even if the system-wide average remains low. This aligns with the "Technical Sovereignty" goal of preventing hidden deep complexities.

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> This change will likely cause the "Health Index" to drop from 100% to a lower value (e.g., 99% or 98%) until the reported high-complexity files are simplified.

## Proposed Changes

### Support Agents

#### [MODIFY] [penalty_engine.py](file:///c:/Users/joaovitormagdaleno/Documents/GitHub/Personas_Agentes/src_local/agents/Support/penalty_engine.py)

Update [_calc_ceiling](file:///c:/Users/joaovitormagdaleno/Documents/GitHub/Personas_Agentes/src_local/agents/Support/penalty_engine.py#28-38) to detect if any file in `map_data` has `complexity > 15` and is a "Functional" component (not DOC/INTERFACE/TEST).
If such files exist, the ceiling will be capped at 99 (or 100 - peak_count).

```python
        # Entropy Peaks: Individual files exceeding the sovereignty threshold (15)
        peak_count = sum(1 for f, i in map_data.items() 
                         if i.get("complexity", 1) > 15 
                         and i.get("component_type") not in ["DOC", "INTERFACE", "TEST"])
        
        total_impact = (loss_count + shallow_count + peak_count)
```

